<br>
I got a 25 set of Pentels, and some Bristol board (as was recommended)<br>
<br>
anyone know any techniques? how would i go about doing detail? (they're rather wide)<br>
blending methods?<br>
overlapping colours? <p>Disclaimer: All opinions voiced by Lina may potentially be only so-much-B.S.
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/27/01 6:50:03 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: got some oil pastels. now what?</span><hr size=1> I haven't used pastels since like grade 10, so that was years ago.  As far as blending techniques, you can use paper towels or your finger, although the later of the two hurts more.  AS well, it's good to get those wrapped pointy paper things from ther art store.  I don't know how to describe them.  They look like a pencil, but it's just paper rolled up super tight with a point on one end.  Those are good for doing smaller detail.  Make sure you use the non-smooth/shiny side of your bristol board (if there is one).  In high school, we always used construction paper because it has more of a tooth on it, and you can get cool effects by using bright colours on gray paper.  As far as overlapping goes, use the lightest/brightest colour first and then add the darker tones into it.  It's hard to lay a dark colour down, and then try to blend in a highlight.  You'd have to just sort of scribble really hard to get it lighter, and sometimes other colours don't like to blend with each other.  White, however, can usually work I think.  I'm kind of rusty...  I haven't used them in so long!  Anywho...  Good luck. <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
